"UGA makes my heart happy.”

Marina Martinez, a Destination Dawg, will complete her UGA journey later this week. During her time here, Marina has brought joy to campus while teaching her peers what life is like with Down syndrome. Destination Dawgs invites students with intellectual disabilities to attend UGA for two years and learn life skills, independent living and career development.

In addition to her Destination Dawgs classes, Marina has studied marketing, PR, advertising and journalism. @ugafacs @ihdduga

“I have always enjoyed being with people in the disability community. My mom works as a special educator, so I learned a lot about it growing up. My goal is to go to occupational therapy school, which I discovered last spring. Being an OT will give me the opportunity to work with a wide variety of people and help individuals gain more independence. I had a really hard time making a choice on my major, so I went with my gut on what I was passionate about and the rest unfolded along the way.”

Rachel Henderson, a senior special education major and Digital Dawg, has found her place and nurtured her passion for loving people as a communications intern for Java Joy, a mobile coffee cart service started by Extra Special People Inc. After graduation, she plans to take a gap year before attending occupational therapy school in 2023.
